** ( setTimeout() ):

- function in JavaScript that allows you to schedule
  the execution of a function, after an amount of time ( milliseconds )

- The delay set in setTimeout() isn't always exact, because, 
  the JavaScript runtime environment (like a browser or Node.js) might be busy, 
  causing the function to run slightly later.

- SetTimeout, is one of the many asynchronous functions 

( Syntax ):

setTimeout( callback or function , delay );
  

( Example (1) Using a Callback ):

function sayHello(){ window.alert("Hello"); }

setTimeout( sayHello, 3000 ); //Outputs: Hello after 3secs 


( Example (2) Using a Literal Function & using Arrow Expression  ):

setTimeout(
function(){ console.log('Hello World') }    
,3000    
); //Outputs: Hello after 3secs ( Same thing )

setTimeout(
() => console.log('Hello World') 
,3000    
); //Outputs: Hello after 3secs ( Same thing )



** ( Synchronous & Asynchronous ):

- Synchronous...
• Executes line by line consecutively in a sequential manner
• Code that waits for an operation to complete

- Asynchronous...
• Allows multiple operations to be performed at the same time w/o waiting 
• Doesn't block execution flow and allows other programs to continue 
( use cases: I/O operations, Network Requests, Async/Await )

( Example of Synchronous ):

console.log("Task 1");
console.log("Task 2");
console.log("Task 3");

// Explanation of the Example: 
// It executes line by line, Task 2 will not output until Task 1 is complete

( Example of Asynchronous ):

function func1(callback){

setTimeout( 
  function(){ 
    console.log("Task1"); 
    callback()
  }    
  ,3000
);

}

function func2(){
 console.log("Task2");
 console.log("Task3");
 console.log("Task4");
}

func1(func2);

// Explanation of the Example: 
// • func1 is invoked & func2 is passed as an argument 
// • using setTimeout, After 3 Secs, it will Output: "Task1" 
// • then the callback ( func2 ) is now invoked, Outputting 
//   "Task 2", "Task 3", "Task 4" Synchronously           